The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                       7                                                                                                        
	New Delhi: India scored four second-half goals as they routed hosts Belgium 6-0 in the third and final hockey Test to clinch the series 2-0 at Wellington, Brussels. India had won the second match 3-2 after a 3-3 draw in the opening game. On Friday, India scored through Sandeep Singh (18, 70), Danish Mujtaba (29), Dhananjay Mahadik (44), Tushar Khandker (45) and Sarvanjit Singh (63). India now travel to Paris where they play three Tests against France.        
	New Delhi: Somdev Dev Varman has entered the singles semi-finals of the Aptos ATP Challenger in the US with a hard-earned 7-5, 4-6, 6-0 win over Briton Alex Bogdanovic. Somdev will now take on American third seed Donald Young.        
	New York: Serena Williams needs surgery on her right foot after cutting it on broken glass at a restaurant. The WTA Tour said Saturday that Serena, who injured herself last week, will miss three tournaments in the lead up to the US Open.        
	Kochi: The Kerala Athletics Association Saturday hit out at the Union and state governments as well as the national governing body for neglecting athletes from the state.        
	Reno: Jeev Milkha Singh turned in a steady three-under 69 as he rose to tied 17th after Round II at the US PGA Tours Reno-Tahoe Open golf meet. Shiv Kapur, however, missed the cut after a disastrous 76.        
	New Delhi: The Indian Boxing Federation has suspended five referees and a judge for one year, penalising them for poor performance (that) cost some pugilists dearly at the just-concluded Senior Mens National Championships.        
	Revel (France): Alexandre Vinokourov has won the 13th stage of the Tour de France in a breakaway as Andy Schleck of Luxembourg retained his half-minute lead over two-time champion Alberto Contador.        
	Karachi: Pakistan can forget playing host any time soon as the ICC does not plan a review of the security situation in the country until the end of this year, chief executive Haroon Lorgat said.           
	New York: The IOC wants to introduce stricter new rules preventing athletes from keeping their medals when one of their teammates commits a doping offence after seven teammates of disgraced US sprinter Marion Jones won an appeal allowing them to keep their medals from the 2000 Sydney Olympics.          
	 Rome: Serie B side Ancona and 20 teams from the Italian lower divisions were blocked from competing in the coming season on Friday because of their financial problems.                                                                                                                                                       
